## Multi-Tool Deduplication
1. Normalize by (file_path, line_number, secret_type)
2. Same secret from multiple tools → merge, combine evidence, use most specific detector
3. Secrets in git history not in current files → still flag (in history means exploitable)

## Output Format

Return a JSON array of findings:
```json
{
  "id": "SECRETS-F<NNN>",
  "title": "Hardcoded <type>",
  "description": "Found <type> in source code",
  "severity": "CRITICAL | HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW",
  "confidence": "HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW",
  "category": "secrets",
  "cwe_id": "CWE-798",
  "location": {"file": "relative/path", "line_start": 10, "line_end": 10, "snippet": "REDACTED first4****last4"},
  "evidence": "Rule: <rule>, Entropy: <value>, Tool(s): <tools>",
  "source": "tool | llm-review | both",
  "source_tool": "gitleaks | trufflehog | null",
  "remediation": {"description": "Remove secret, rotate credential, use secrets manager", "effort": "LOW", "priority": "P0|P1", "code_suggestion": null},
  "false_positive_risk": "LOW | MEDIUM | HIGH",
  "false_positive_reasoning": "Assessment",
  "tags": ["secrets", "credential-type"]
}
```

**IMPORTANT**: NEVER include the actual secret value. Redact to first 4 and last 4 characters (e.g., AKIA****WXYZ).

Return ONLY the JSON array of findings. No other text.
